      "text": "S. 15"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7beef8dc4d4d19b6",
      "text": "There will be many things to say about this extreme form of spontaneous mass. It is not quite as spontaneous where it originates, in its very core, as it appears to be. But everywhere else, apart from the five or ten or twelve people from whom it started, it really is. Once it exists, it wants to consist of more. The urge to grow is the first and foremost characteristic of the mass. It wants to capture everyone who is within its reach. Whoever is shaped like a human being can join it. The natural mass is the open mass: its growth has no limit at all. Houses, doors and locks it does not recognize; those who block themselves before it are suspicious to it. \"Open\" is to be understood here in every meaning, it is it everywhere and in every direction. The open mass exists as long as it grows. Its decay begins as soon as it stops growing."
    }
